00:15:37,740 --> 00:15:38,580
It's uncanny.

232
00:15:38,580 --> 00:15:41,080
The standard account tells us what the code is doing.

233
00:15:41,400 --> 00:15:46,040
It totally fails to explain why it works across every conceivable domain of reality.

234
00:15:46,140 --> 00:15:50,680
The universality of the math strongly suggests it is not a human invention at all.

235
00:15:51,040 --> 00:15:51,900
It's a discovery.

236
00:15:52,120 --> 00:15:52,620
A discovery.

237
00:15:52,620 --> 00:15:53,220
Yeah.

238
00:15:53,700 --> 00:15:59,540
It suggests that dynamic programming is capturing a fundamental underlying geometry of how systems

239
00:15:59,540 --> 00:16:00,060
evolve.

240
00:16:00,720 --> 00:16:01,480
Think of it this way.

241
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:07,700
If the manual for your kitchen toaster perfectly describes the orbital mechanics of a distant

242
00:16:07,700 --> 00:16:12,760
galaxy, you have to admit you aren't just looking at a toaster manual anymore.

243
00:16:12,760 --> 00:16:13,160
Huh.

244
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:14,860
That's a perfect way to put it.

245
00:16:15,360 --> 00:16:20,160
And that realization is what launches us out of standard computer science and into the

246
00:16:20,160 --> 00:16:22,100
absolute heart of Flicksheen's paper.

247
00:16:22,860 --> 00:16:25,800
This brings us to the RSVP paradigm shift.

248
00:16:26,220 --> 00:16:29,660
RSVP stands for the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

249
00:16:30,220 --> 00:16:30,540
Okay.

250
00:16:30,720 --> 00:16:31,520
That's a lot of words.

251
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:32,100
It is.

252
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:36,240
This is the unifying theoretical framework Flicksheen has constructed.

253
00:16:36,680 --> 00:16:41,740
The central premise is that we need to entirely stop thinking about computers executing discrete

254
00:16:41,740 --> 00:16:42,560
lines of code.

255
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:48,400
Instead, both physical systems and computational algorithms evolve over what the text calls

256
00:16:48,400 --> 00:16:49,980
admissible manifolds.

257
00:16:50,340 --> 00:16:54,580
Let's break down admissible manifolds so you, the listener, can actually visualize this.

258
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:58,900
A manifold, broadly speaking, is just a mathematical space, right?

259
00:16:58,960 --> 00:16:59,780
Like a landscape.

260
00:17:00,160 --> 00:17:00,460
Yes.

261
00:17:00,460 --> 00:17:06,280
Think of it as a vast, multidimensional terrain that represents every possible state a system

262
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:07,640
could conceivably be in.

263
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:09,900
But the key word here is admissible.

264
00:17:10,580 --> 00:17:11,140
Allowed.

265
00:17:11,320 --> 00:17:11,640
Correct.

266
00:17:11,740 --> 00:17:15,740
Not every path across this terrain is actually possible.

267
00:17:16,240 --> 00:17:21,360
If you are a physical particle, some paths violate the conservation of energy.

268
00:17:21,740 --> 00:17:26,620
If you are an AI playing chess, some paths violate the rules of the game.

269
00:17:27,040 --> 00:17:33,040
If you are a biological organism, some paths lead immediately to starvation and death.

270
00:17:33,380 --> 00:17:38,360
So the admissible trajectories are the paths that obey the structural constraints of the

271
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:38,700
system.

272
00:17:38,700 --> 00:17:43,400
They are the paths that keep the system viable, alive, functioning.

273
00:17:43,400 --> 00:17:45,100
They are the allowed futures.

274
00:17:45,100 --> 00:17:45,720
Okay.

275
00:17:45,720 --> 00:17:46,220
Okay.

276
00:17:46,220 --> 00:17:48,720
So reality is a landscape of allowed futures.

277
00:17:48,720 --> 00:17:54,100
To navigate this landscape, fliction establishes what they call a fundamental identification.

278
00:17:54,340 --> 00:18:05,260
The text takes the three boring standard components of a dynamic programming algorithm and maps them directly onto physical fields in this RSVP universe.

279
00:18:05,260 --> 00:18:08,260
This trinity is really the core of the whole paper.

280
00:18:08,260 --> 00:18:09,260
Let's take these one by one.

281
00:18:09,260 --> 00:18:11,260
First, the value function.

282
00:18:11,260 --> 00:18:15,020
In standard DP, the value function is just the score you assign to a state, right?

283
00:18:15,020 --> 00:18:15,920
High score is good.

284
00:18:15,920 --> 00:18:16,760
Low score is bad.

285
00:18:16,760 --> 00:18:22,880
Fliction maps this to a physical field called the scalar accessibility potential, represented

286
00:18:22,880 --> 00:18:24,420
by the Greek letter phi.

287
00:18:24,420 --> 00:18:30,600
The massive shift here is moving from a discrete number in a spreadsheet to a continuous physical

288
00:18:30,600 --> 00:18:31,120
field.

289
00:18:32,120 --> 00:18:36,080
In RSVP, phi isn't just a point system for winning a video game.

290
00:18:36,540 --> 00:18:42,940
It is a physical geometric measure of how much of the future remains open, accessible, and favorable

291
00:18:42,940 --> 00:18:43,800
to the system.

292
00:18:43,800 --> 00:18:48,340
So if I am in a state with a high phi, it means I am standing on a vantage point where

293
00:18:48,340 --> 00:18:51,800
I have a massive horizon of highly rewarding possibilities ahead of me.

294
00:18:52,460 --> 00:18:56,920
But if I am in a state with a low phi, my future is constrained.

295
00:18:57,080 --> 00:18:58,160
I'm backed into a corner.

296
00:18:58,460 --> 00:18:58,740
Yes.

297
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:03,560
The value function is a literal landscape of potential energy.

298
00:19:04,120 --> 00:19:05,480
Now let's look at the second component.

299
00:19:05,960 --> 00:19:08,480
In a computer algorithm, you have a policy.

300
00:19:08,760 --> 00:19:08,980
Right.

301
00:19:08,980 --> 00:19:13,860
This is the logical rule, the iphon statement that tells the computer what action to take

302
00:19:13,860 --> 00:19:14,280
next.

303
00:19:14,900 --> 00:19:18,440
Fliction maps the policy to the vector flow field, or v.

304
00:19:18,840 --> 00:19:24,260
So the scalar field phi is the shape of the landscape, and the vector field v is the actual

305
00:19:24,260 --> 00:19:25,800
direction of movement.

306
00:19:26,220 --> 00:19:26,720
Exactly.

307
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:29,680
The policy is no longer seen as a line of code.

308
00:19:30,100 --> 00:19:32,280
It is a physical tangent vector.

309
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:38,020
It is the directional arrow pointing exactly along the path that most efficiently navigates

310
00:19:38,020 --> 00:19:40,240
the gradient of the potential field phi.

311
00:19:40,460 --> 00:19:44,980
And optimal policy is just the natural flow of a system seeking the highest accessible

312
00:19:44,980 --> 00:19:45,480
future.

313
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:45,960
Yes.

314
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:51,040
And the third part of the trinity in dp, we have the admissibility volume.

315
00:19:51,580 --> 00:19:55,020
That's the sheer number of viable paths left to take.

316
00:19:55,720 --> 00:19:59,500
Fliction maps this to the entropy field, represented by s.

317
00:19:59,500 --> 00:20:02,840
It is the logarithmic volume of open futures.

318
00:20:02,840 --> 00:20:08,700
We have to be very careful here to distinguish between the value phi and the entropy s, because

319
00:20:08,700 --> 00:20:10,240
they are not the same thing at all.

320
00:20:10,300 --> 00:20:11,020
Not at all.

321
00:20:11,160 --> 00:20:15,980
You could be in a state with an incredibly high phi, meaning there is an astronomically

322
00:20:15,980 --> 00:20:20,720
high reward available to you, but getting that reward requires you to walk a tightrope

323
00:20:20,720 --> 00:20:21,840
over an active volcano.

324
00:20:22,060 --> 00:20:22,380
Right.

325
00:20:22,520 --> 00:20:26,180
There is only one specific narrow path to get the prize.

326
00:20:26,300 --> 00:20:26,440
Yeah.

327
00:20:26,440 --> 00:20:28,040
If you deviate by an inch, you die.

328
00:20:28,040 --> 00:20:28,560
Exactly.

329
00:20:28,880 --> 00:20:35,460
That state has high phi, meaning high reward potential, but extremely low s, very low entropy,

330
00:20:35,780 --> 00:20:37,320
very few viable paths.

331
00:20:37,760 --> 00:20:44,000
But conversely, you could be in a state with a mediocre phi, but massive s.

332
00:20:44,220 --> 00:20:44,600
Yes.

333
00:20:44,800 --> 00:20:50,280
Like, you might not be on the path to becoming a billionaire, but you have thousands of different

334
00:20:50,280 --> 00:20:54,620
safe, acceptable, middle-class career paths available to you.

335
00:20:54,940 --> 00:20:57,120
High entropy means high flexibility.

336
00:20:57,120 --> 00:20:58,400
You have room to breathe.

337
00:20:58,620 --> 00:21:00,260
Here's where it gets really interesting.

338
00:21:00,660 --> 00:21:05,120
I want to offer an analogy here to help you, the listener, really lock this trinity into

339
00:21:05,120 --> 00:21:05,580
your mind.

340
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:09,580
Imagine a massive mountain and it's pouring rain.

341
00:21:09,840 --> 00:21:10,060
Oh.

342
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:11,940
The water is trying to find its way down.

343
00:21:12,240 --> 00:21:17,600
The mountain itself, the physical height, the slopes, the dips and valleys, that is the

344
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:19,860
scalar accessibility potential find.

345
00:21:20,020 --> 00:21:22,940
It dictates the potential energy and the shape of the landscape.

346
00:21:23,200 --> 00:21:23,520
Perfect.

347
00:21:23,520 --> 00:21:28,980
The actual direction the water naturally rushes based on gravity, the specific currents cutting

348
00:21:28,980 --> 00:21:34,560
through the dirt that is the vector flow field, it's the policy the water follows.

349
00:21:34,720 --> 00:21:35,040
Right.

350
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:40,840
And finally, how wide the river channel is, how much room the water has to slosh around

351
00:21:40,840 --> 00:21:45,280
left and right, exploring the banks while still generally flowing downward.

352
00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:47,540
That is the entropy field, S.

353
00:21:47,840 --> 00:21:50,860
That analogy holds up beautifully under the math.

354
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:57,820
When a dynamic programming algorithm runs, it is essentially acting as a divine cartographer.

355
00:21:58,180 --> 00:21:58,900
Oh, I like that.

356
00:21:59,120 --> 00:22:06,220
It is simultaneously calculating the exact topographical shape of the mountain, which is phi, defining

357
00:22:06,220 --> 00:22:11,680
the precise currents of the rivers, which is V, and measuring the exact width

358
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:13,840
of the floodplains, which is S.

359
00:22:14,440 --> 00:22:19,120
There is another concept from standard DP that gets translated into physical reality here.

360
00:22:19,300 --> 00:22:23,020
And it's a concept that always felt completely artificial to me.

361
00:22:23,240 --> 00:22:23,700
Which one?

362
00:22:23,900 --> 00:22:26,540
The discount factor, represented by gamma.

363
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:33,160
In computer science or economics, you use a discount factor because a reward today is worth

364
00:22:33,160 --> 00:22:34,500
more than a reward tomorrow.

365
00:22:34,620 --> 00:22:34,940
Right.

366
00:22:34,940 --> 00:22:36,200
It's a financial concept.

367
00:22:36,560 --> 00:22:38,860
A dollar today is better than a dollar in 10 years.

368
00:22:39,500 --> 00:22:42,580
But Flitchin claims gamma isn't a financial hack at all.

369
00:22:43,040 --> 00:22:45,040
It's a physical property of the universe.

370
00:22:45,520 --> 00:22:46,840
Let's look at the mechanics of that.

371
00:22:46,980 --> 00:22:51,860
In the RSVP framework, the discount factor represents the system's coherence length.

372
00:22:51,980 --> 00:22:52,640
Coherence length.

373
00:22:53,020 --> 00:22:58,220
Meaning, like, how far into the future the system can actually maintain its structural integrity.

374
00:22:58,760 --> 00:22:59,320
Precisely.

375
00:22:59,600 --> 00:23:04,840
If a system has a gamma approaching 1, it means the system is highly stable.

376
00:23:04,940 --> 00:23:10,800
It can plan for the distant future because its structural coherence extends far through time.

377
00:23:11,380 --> 00:23:14,360
It cares about rewards that are a hundred steps away.

378
00:23:14,580 --> 00:23:18,760
But if a system is highly volatile, its gamma drops towards zero.

379
00:23:19,120 --> 00:23:23,760
It completely discounts tomorrow because tomorrow is entirely unpredictable.

380
00:23:24,200 --> 00:23:26,040
Its coherence length has shrunk.

381
00:23:26,040 --> 00:23:29,960
It only optimizes for immediate short-term survival.

382
00:23:29,960 --> 00:23:38,560
So when a programmer arbitrarily types gamma equals 0.9 into their code, they aren't just tweaking a financial parameter.

383
00:23:38,800 --> 00:23:43,240
They are mathematically simulating the temporal decay wave of a physical system.

384
00:23:43,240 --> 00:23:48,520
The algorithm is physically behaving like a decaying wave in the scalar vector plenum.

385
00:23:49,100 --> 00:23:53,160
This realization requires us to fundamentally shift our entire perspective.

386
00:23:53,520 --> 00:24:02,220
If a state in a computer program is actually a geometric position in a continuous physical field, we have to completely rethink what computation actually is.

387
00:24:02,300 --> 00:24:02,620
We do.

388
00:24:02,620 --> 00:24:14,400
When a computer remembers a number in a dynamic programming table, it isn't just etching data onto a silicon hard drive, which raises the question, what is memory in a geometric universe?

389
00:24:14,900 --> 00:24:21,620
And that question leads us to what is arguably the most profound philosophical assertion in Fliction's monograph.

390
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:26,680
It's the concept of memoization as ontological compression.

391
00:24:27,060 --> 00:24:28,600
Let's define the terms for the listener.

392
00:24:29,360 --> 00:24:31,440
Memoization is a computer science term.

393
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:33,540
It basically means making a memo.

394
00:24:34,620 --> 00:24:41,800
When an algorithm calculates a complex equation, instead of throwing the answer away, it writes it down in a lookup table.

395
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:46,860
The next time it encounters that exact equation, it doesn't do the math.

396
00:24:47,100 --> 00:24:48,300
It just reads the memo.

397
00:24:48,880 --> 00:24:49,540
It's caching.

398
00:24:49,860 --> 00:24:51,800
That is the functional definition, yes.

399
00:24:51,900 --> 00:24:54,240
But Fliction says this is not just caching data.

400
00:24:54,380 --> 00:24:56,380
It is ontological compression.

401
00:24:56,380 --> 00:25:02,080
It is ontological meaning related to the fundamental nature of being, of reality itself.

402
00:25:02,480 --> 00:25:06,640
How does saving a number in a table equate to compressing reality?

403
00:25:07,140 --> 00:25:11,660
To understand this, we have to explore Fliction's concept of dynamic equivalence.

404
00:25:11,980 --> 00:25:13,100
Let's build a thought experiment.

405
00:25:13,400 --> 00:25:13,580
Yeah.

406
00:25:13,580 --> 00:25:17,840
Imagine you and I agree to meet at a specific coffee shop at exactly noon.

407
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:21,880
We both arrive on time, and we both have exactly $10 in our pockets.

408
00:25:22,040 --> 00:25:22,160
Right.

409
00:25:22,500 --> 00:25:25,980
But our histories of how we got there are radically different.

410
00:25:26,420 --> 00:25:26,720
Okay.

411
00:25:26,940 --> 00:25:33,320
Let's say I woke up late, I rushed to the subway, almost lost my wallet, and then I sprinted the last three blocks.

412
00:25:33,320 --> 00:25:34,680
Sounds stressful.

413
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:42,520
And let's say I woke up early, took a leisurely stroll through a park, stopped to read a book, and walked into the shop.

414
00:25:42,800 --> 00:25:46,260
Okay, so our past trajectories are vastly different.

415
00:25:46,800 --> 00:25:47,500
Very different.

416
00:25:47,720 --> 00:25:56,220
But from the exact moment we're both standing at the counter, from the perspective of our future admissibility, does our past matter?

417
00:25:56,560 --> 00:25:57,080
Well, no.

418
00:25:57,440 --> 00:25:58,240
We both have $10.

419
00:25:58,940 --> 00:26:01,560
We can both buy the exact same cup of coffee.

420
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,920
We have the same options of where to sit.

421
00:26:04,160 --> 00:26:04,500
Exactly.

422
00:26:05,220 --> 00:26:10,520
Our future admissibility sets our phi and s fields going forward are mathematically identical.

423
00:26:11,060 --> 00:26:16,280
Focliction defines this by saying our two distinct histories are dynamically equivalent.

424
00:26:16,600 --> 00:26:22,440
Because the future possibilities are identical, the pasts are mathematically indistinguishable going forward.

425
00:26:22,820 --> 00:26:24,500
And here is the ontological leap.

426
00:26:24,500 --> 00:26:31,420
The universe, or the optimal algorithm, does not merely forget our distinct histories out of computational convenience.

427
00:26:32,560 --> 00:26:39,160
The math suggests that the past histories literally cease to exist as independent geometric entities.

428
00:26:39,480 --> 00:26:39,860
Wait, really?

429
00:26:40,220 --> 00:26:40,540
Yes.

430
00:26:40,980 --> 00:26:45,020
The two distinct timelines collapse into a single point.

431
00:26:45,660 --> 00:26:47,080
That point is the state.

432
00:26:47,540 --> 00:26:53,660
The state is defined purely as the equivalence class of all histories that share the exact same future.

433
00:26:53,660 --> 00:26:54,380
Hold on.

434
00:26:54,660 --> 00:26:55,720
Let me push back on this.

435
00:26:55,840 --> 00:26:59,700
Because this sounds like we are saying reality literally deletes the past.

436
00:26:59,860 --> 00:27:08,720
Are you saying that when a computer uses a lookup table, when it memoizes a value, it is not taking a clever programming shortcut.

437
00:27:09,300 --> 00:27:15,700
It is accurately simulating a physical truth that reality actively compresses redundant timelines.

438
00:27:16,160 --> 00:27:19,260
The math actually supports this literal interpretation.

439
00:27:19,260 --> 00:27:23,040
Flitchin provides a rigorous proof called the compression theorem.

440
00:27:23,280 --> 00:27:24,000
How does that work?

441
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:26,260
Think about the sheer volume of history.

442
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:34,000
If you track every single possible branching choice in a complex system, the tree of histories explodes exponentially.

443
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:38,240
It goes to infinity so fast that no universe could contain the information.

444
00:27:38,500 --> 00:27:39,800
The combinatorial explosion.

445
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:40,200
Right.

446
00:27:40,740 --> 00:27:52,180
But if you apply the rule of dynamic equivalence, compressing every history that shares a future into a single node, that infinite exploding tree collapses into a polynomial state space.

447
00:27:52,780 --> 00:27:56,000
It shrinks into a manageable geometric object.

448
00:27:56,700 --> 00:28:00,080
The universe survives by constantly compressing its own history.

449
00:28:00,220 --> 00:28:00,560
Yes.

450
00:28:00,800 --> 00:28:05,180
And when this compression happens, the timelines don't just vanish into the ether.

451
00:28:05,180 --> 00:28:12,280
When the branching histories are pruned and collapsed, they leave behind what Flitchin calls a projection residue.

452
00:28:12,760 --> 00:28:14,800
What exactly is a projection residue?

453
00:28:15,220 --> 00:28:19,620
Think of it as a permanent geometric imprint left on the admissibility field.

454
00:28:19,900 --> 00:28:27,180
The specific numbers stored in the dynamic programming table, the value phi and the tangent vector v, are the projection residues.

455
00:28:27,180 --> 00:28:35,720
They are the dense, aggregated footprint of all the collapsed pasts that led to that specific configuration of future potential.

456
00:28:36,380 --> 00:28:37,680
Let me try a physical analogy.

457
00:28:38,240 --> 00:28:42,640
If you take a flat piece of paper and you fold it in half, you are compressing it.

458
00:28:42,760 --> 00:28:46,520
If you unfold the paper, the paper is flat again, but the crease remains.

459
00:28:47,020 --> 00:28:48,020
The crease is permanent.

460
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:50,300
The crease is the projection residue.

461
00:28:50,540 --> 00:28:52,540
That is a brilliant way to visualize it.

462
00:28:52,540 --> 00:28:58,480
The memorization table in a computer, the lookup table, is essentially a map of the universe's creases.

463
00:28:58,760 --> 00:29:04,520
It is a record of where reality has folded its own history to maintain computational viability.

464
00:29:05,040 --> 00:29:11,140
But if these states are just compressed creases of future possibility, how do they relate to each other?

465
00:29:11,760 --> 00:29:15,660
A table of numbers is discrete, but reality is continuous.

466
00:29:16,200 --> 00:29:21,520
How do we stitch all of these folded pieces of space back together without tearing the fabric?

467
00:29:21,520 --> 00:29:27,540
Answering that requires a transition into a very specific, highly advanced branch of mathematics.

468
00:29:28,100 --> 00:29:32,060
This is where Fliction introduces the geometry of optimization.

469
00:29:32,580 --> 00:29:39,040
I am going to act as the proxy for the listener right now, because when I read this section of the paper, I felt a genuine sense of dread.

470
00:29:39,360 --> 00:29:40,580
It's definitely dense.

